title="Jon Sterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
type="local"
href="marcelofiore.xml"
addr="marcelofiore"
title="Marcelo Fiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is called <fr:em><fr:strong>infinite</fr:strong></fr:em> when it is not <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00LX.xml"
addr="jms-00LX"
title="Finite set">finite</fr:link> in the sense of <fr:ref
addr="jms-00LX"
href="jms-00LX.xml"
taxon="Definition" />.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:p>The basic axioms of set theory that we have learned in this course so far do not in fact guarantee the existence of any <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00M1.xml"
addr="jms-00M1"
title="Infinite set">infinite sets</fr:link>. For this reason, one usually adds the <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00M1.xml"
addr="jms-00M1"
title="Infinite set">axiom of infinity</fr:link> below to set theory.</fr:p><fr:tree
